               aith hee, cum aliud agitur, &amp; aliud fingitur;
               
when one thing appears in the fact,
and another thing is hid in the heart.
Yet even this, if it bee for the good of
some, and the hurt and hinderance of
none, I dare not pronounce to be simply
unlawfull. Such a deceit is that
which Nurses use for the stilling of
their children; or Physicians, for the
healing of their Patients. Such did our
Prophet himselfe use, when for the saving
of his life hee fained himself mad,
among the Philistines, 1. Sam. 21. 13.
And hitherto are those words of S. Paul
by some referred, For as much as I was
crafty, I took you by guile, 2. Cor. 12. 16.
