grievous a sinne it is in the opinion of
the very Paynims themselves, and how
dangerous to the Common-wealth, to
neglect and omit the punishment of
notorious malefactors, whereby the
offences of particular men are made
the sinnes of the whole State, and draw
the wrath and punishment of God upon

the same: And as upon the whole
State, so chiefly upon his person and
posterity to whose place and office it
belongs to see justice done. It is a true
